Case Study Scenario

As a geospatial consultant for farmers in the Central Valley, you often work with client-provided datasets, including both raster and vector formats. Sometimes you inherit data from previous projects done by other consultants, such as statewide crop data from 2014. In this case study, you’ll have to practice rasterizing polygon data and do some summary statistics. You’ll also brush up on your ModelBuilder and Python skills, as you know the importance of replicability (and the importance of saving time by not having to start from scratch for all of your projects around the Valley!). It’s been a while since you’ve used ModelBuilder and Python, so by the time this project is over, you’ll remember the benefits of each, and where to use different data types for different needs.

This first half of Case Study 2 focuses on converting between raster and vector formats and the ModelBuilder tool in ArcGIS Pro, a drag and drop style approach to geoprocessing.

Instructions

Part 1: Rasters and Vectors

This lab focuses on the difference between raster data (like imagery) and vector data (points, lines, polygons), nicely summarized in Figure 1. Different scenarios may call for converting between data types. We will walk through converting from raster to vector and vector to raster in this lab. You will use ModelBuilder and ArcPy for these conversions. Some processes are quick and easy, just one or two steps. The more proficient you get with ArcGIS Pro, especially if you go into a GIS role, the more complex geoprocessing you will find yourself doing…


ModelBuilder: This drag and drop approach to building workflows in ArcGIS offers visual understandings [1,2]. ModelBuilder allows you to create custom tools for multi-step geoprocessing tasks. ModelBuilder is a tool for communicating workflows to non-GISers who may not be familiar with GIS jargon. These visualizations are fantastic for communicating project tasks and workflows with upper management.

ModelBuilder isn’t just a pretty picture of your workflow, however. Each shape corresponds to an input, a geoprocessing tool, or an output. The user specifies the parameters before running the model. Where is the data coming from? What parameters (settings) does each step need? Where do you want the outputs to go, and what do you want them to be called?


Unfortunately, the bigger the project in ModelBuilder, the messier the visuals. ModelBuilder has limits, mainly that it is GIS-centric. It won’t (can’t) do much outside of GIS software and datasets. Python can! This well-known programming language has been built into ArcGIS software with its own GIS specific package, ArcPy. This is a Python package of GIS tools and workflows built directly into the software.

Python allows you to reach beyond the confines of ArcGIS Pro and do external tasks, such as moving files around.

Watch this short video about Python packages https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AjYeGIsZpuk

A Note on Data Management
WARNING: Raster datasets are often large! Depending on how they were encoded, they may compress well. You need to extract all .zip files in order for your files to be read by ArcGIS Pro, Excel or most any other program. Be mindful of your disk space, because some of these rasters expand to hundreds of megabytes when unzipped.

You will need at least 2GB of free space for this lab.

Part 2: Raster Data Exploration

Often, you’ll find rasters where each pixel represents a continuous variable, like a height, or color value. Digital Elevation Models (DEMs) are one example of a spatial dataset comprising continuous variables. A DEM is a raster, where each pixel represents a specific elevation (a height above some datum, usually Mean Sea Level [MSL]). Let’s explore a small slice of the GTOPO30 DEM , a 30-arc-second global DEM that was produced by USGS-EROS in 1996 [3,4].



• Download all of the class data to your Classfiles folder for Case Study 2-1 and extract the folder.

2.1 Raster data in a spreadsheet Let’s explore a slice of the GTOPO30 DEM. Let’s first open a plain-text, matrix representation of this data.
• Open the GTOPO30 folder.
• Open GTOPO30_ca_clip.csv in Microsoft Excel.
• Select all cells in the spreadsheet
    o Hint: use Ctrl+A to select all cells
• Apply a color scale conditional formatting rule so that each cell gets a color according to its value.
    o Hint: Use the conditional formatting tool in the main ribbon (see Fig. 4).
    o Try changing through several different color schemes.

2.2.2 Raster data in ArcGIS Pro Now, we’ll open a GeoTIFF encoding of the same data file. GeoTIFF is a popular public domain extension of the lossless TIFF image format. Most of the raster data you will find on the web is available as GeoTIFF. For more about what GeoTIFF is, read the following articles about raster data basics from ESRI [3,4] and the following article from NASA, EartData [5].

• Open ArcGIS Pro and create your Project for Case Study 2-1 - double check that your Location starts with Z:. If not, hand key it in so that it matches Z: through 180…(yours wont say instructor!)


• Add GTOPO30_ca_clip.tif to your workspace. The file is located in the GTOPO30 folder. If the software asks if you’d like to calculate statistics, say yes! It wont take long.
    o Hint: In ArcGIS, there are multiple ways to do the same thing. You can drag and drop some types of files into your map space from Windows Explorer!
• Add cnty24k09_1_poly.shp to your workspace through Add Data. The file is located in the Shapefiles folder.
    o Wait, why can’t you drag and drop shapefiles? They’re a whole collection of individual files that collectively make up a single shapefile. In Windows Explorer you’ll see lots of “parts” for cnty24k09_1_poly.shp. If you add it in through Add Data in ArcGIS Pro, you only see one because it packages them all together nicely.



• Add osm_173351856.shp to your workspace. The file is located in the Shapefiles folder.
    o Which boundary does this shapefile represent? Hint: Check the attribute table by right clicking on the layer to open the table.
• Turn off your basemap if needed (Did you notice if the Topographic layer shows up by default?)

Part 3: Vector to Raster

You will also find rasters that represent categorical variables, such as land cover type. In this case, pixel values represent some quality of the underlying surface (e.g. 10 may correspond to bare soil, 20 – asphalt, 21 – grass, 22 – shrub land, etc.) Most land cover datasets are distributed as rasters (e.g. NLCD, CDL, GLC) [6, 7, 8]. However, occasionally you find land cover datasets distributed as shapefiles. In this exercise, we will utilize the 2014 Statewide Crop Mapping Overview [9]to explore how the use of different parameters affect vector-to-raster conversions.

3.1 Review: Vector Project and Vector Clip
• Start from a new, blank template (save your work from the previous session and start from a fresh slate in a whole new project. Top left corner Project-> New->Blank Template-> Map).
• Extract the atlas_i15_CropMapping2014.zip folder into your working directory, and load i15_Crop_Mapping_2014_Final_LandIQonAtlas.shp into your workspace.
• Add cnty24k09_1_poly.shp to your workspace. The file is located in the Shapefiles folder.
• Use the Project (Data Management) tool to change the CRS of cnty24k09_1_poly.shp to match the i15_Crop_Mapping_2014 layer.
    o Hint: You can match up your desired CRS for projection to the CRS of a dataset that is already in your Table of Contents. Remember we did some Projection work in past labs? (see Fig. 5)
• Name this projected file as cnty24k09_poly_6414 for your Output Dataset or Feature Class parameter.
    o Remove the original cnty24k09_1_poly.shp layer from your workspace to avoid mixing up layers.
• Extract (isolate) the Merced County boundary from your projected California boundaries and save it as a separate feature class named: mcd_poly_6414.

Coordinate Reference System information is available for existing layers in the drop down option! Choose the correct layer.

    o Hint: Open the attribute table and select the feature (row) that corresponds to Merced county (OR click on it once in the map so it’s highlighted in blue). Now, right click on the layer name in your ToC and navigate to Data  Export Features. This will open a geoprocessing window where you can set the new layer name. Run.
• Clip the crop cover shapefile to the extent of Merced county using the Clip (Analysis) tool. Name the output file: i15_crop_mcd
• Under layer symbology, assign colors according to the crop category (“Crop2014”). Hint: these are all unique values.

Export a PRODUCTION QUALITY MAP (5 key map elements!) of your clipped crop cover feature class (don’t forget to remove the original statewide crop layer.) Describe your submission in a few sentences. Describe what your map is visualizing. Read the land cover file metadata (source also linked in the References section below) and briefly describe how the dataset was produced.

3.2 Rasterizing polygons with ModelBuilder In this step you will convert your vector land cover dataset to a raster and observe how different input parameters change how the underlying data is represented in the gridded output. For more about “rasterization” (and the reverse process, “vector grids”), refer to the following articles in the ArcGIS documentation: [10, 11, 12, 13].

• Make sure that you have completed the steps in the previous section. You need to have clipped i15_Crop_Mapping_2014_Final_LandIQonAtlas to the Merced county boundary, and the result should have been saved as: i15_crop_mcd.
• Open Model Builder from your Analysis Toolbar Ribbon
• Use the Tools dropdown in the ModelBuilder Diagram Ribbon to add Polygon to Raster (Conversion) tool.



See how the new components are gray? That means we need to set our parameters! Plus, we have a tool (P to R) connected to an Output, but no input, right?

• Double click our Polygon to Raster tool to open the empty Parameters tab
• Select the appropriate i15_crop_mcd input. Notice some fields auto populate. That helps save time, but we still need to change some.
• The “Value field” should correspond to the features in the shapefile that you wish to map onto your pixel values. In this case, we’re going to use the land cover categories present in the “Crop2014” column.
• Hover your mouse over the Output Raster Dataset location. Notice it’s still auto populating to your project folder. We love that! It’s a nice sanity check. Also note the Cellsize in the final row.
• Change your Output Raster Dataset file name to: mcd_crops_[cellsize] where you’ll replace [cellsize] with the default cell size that the tool recommended in Polygon to Raster.

 Don’t use the brackets in the file name- just the numbers!

• For your first run, use the default “Cellsize” and the default “Cell assignment type”
• Click Ok.
• In the ModelBuilder Ribbon, Click Validate. This will make sure we’re not missing anything. If you don’t receive any errors, go ahead and click Run! If your new raster doesn’t show up, check your Table of Contents to see if it is hiding beneath another layer. Still not showing up? Refresh your Geodatabase in your Catalog window and it should pop up!

Export a PRODUCTION QUALITY MAP (all 5 key map elements!) of your crop cover raster and describe your submission in a few sentences. Describe which parameters you used in the polygon-to-raster conversion. Describe how the tool recommends a default cell size. Include a screenshot of your Model.

Going from vector to raster was pretty quick, but what if you had a manager who wanted to see a workflow of ALL of your steps, in a nice visual package?

• Return to Section 3.1.
• Use ModelBuilder to repeat from the 4th bullet of step 3.1 through the end of step 3.2 into ONE seamless Model. Hint: Identify which actions/tools you used in 3.1 and 3.2 first. Pull those into the Model window and build out from there. You’ll need to select MERCED County using the Select Layer by Attribute Tool in your Model, after projecting and before clipping.

Another Hint: If things start looking funky or crowded, use Auto Layout to help you rearrange your Model items.

• Save all of your outputs with _ModBuild on the ends of the file names.
• Save this Model to rerun in the future. Note that when you “save as” the file type is tool. Save as mcd_prj_clip_rasterize. Go to your Catalog and look in the toolbox in your project folder. There is your new custom tool!!

Take a screenshot of your ArcGIS Pro window including the Project folder showing all of the _ModBuild outputs in your geodatabase as well as the full model in the main window.
